nice seminar to the Deming conference to go through the

00:07:53.600 --> 00:07:56.399
information. And if you're interested, you can go to this

00:07:56.399 --> 00:08:01.320
book down project to see all the information. And secondly,

00:08:01.480 --> 00:08:06.320
so recently, you can see a trend of using estimate framework

00:08:06.320 --> 00:08:11.480
following the ICH ENI R1 addendum. So in response that

00:08:11.679 --> 00:08:15.040
noble missing data approach may need to be applied. For

00:08:15.040 --> 00:08:18.079
example, in recent paper, we collaborate with academia

00:08:18.079 --> 00:08:22.399
members for recurrent event data and robustness of missing data.

00:08:22.920 --> 00:08:26.720
All those methods have been implemented as an R package and

00:08:26.720 --> 00:08:31.880
publicly available. So when clinical trials try to apply

00:08:31.880 --> 00:08:35.679
those noble methods to their trial, instead of re-implementing

00:08:35.719 --> 00:08:39.799
other software, maybe we can just apply those R packages

00:08:39.799 --> 00:08:43.760
available to the clinical trial study with the proper manner

00:08:43.840 --> 00:08:47.760
that package has been qualified and tested before it can be used

00:08:47.840 --> 00:08:51.640
for the final results. And as you may be aware, R is also

00:08:51.640 --> 00:08:54.400
widely used for Bayesian statistics with a popular

00:08:54.400 --> 00:08:59.200
package like STAN to be able to handle the Bayesian modeling

00:08:59.200 --> 00:09:02.679
part for hierarchical modeling. And sometimes for the network

00:09:02.679 --> 00:09:06.960
